  "slug": "tarte-aux-pommes",
  "title": "Tarte aux pommes",
  "subtitle": "French open-face apple tart on sweet shortcrust",
  "excerpt": "The French open-face apple tart: a sweet shortcrust shell, a thin layer of apple compote, and overlapping slices of fresh apple on top, brushed with apricot glaze. One 23 cm tart, serving eight.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Marie-Antoine Carême, L'Art de la cuisine française (1833), Project Gutenberg: documents the French apple tart with compote base and sliced-apple fan. Urbain Dubois, La Cuisine Classique (1856), Project Gutenberg (French): gives the apricot-glaze finish. The form is a standard French pâtisserie shape from the early nineteenth century.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tarte aux pommes is a French pâtisserie standard. The base is a sweet shortcrust, the middle is a soft apple compote, and the top is a fan of overlapping fresh apple slices, brushed with warm apricot glaze. The pastry is blind-baked, the compote is cooked on the hob, and the final bake is brief. Just long enough to soften the top slices and let the pastry colour at the edges."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bramley apples cook to a smooth compote and are the choice for the lower layer; firm eating apples (Cox, Braeburn) hold their shape on the top fan. Use both. The contrast is deliberate.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
